{{Japanese name|Matsudaira}}
{{nihongo|'''Morisada Matsudaira'''|松平 保定|Matsudaira Morisada|1926 – 9 Aug 2011}} was a Japanese businessman who was active in historical preservation. The grandson of [[Matsudaira Katamori]], he spent a fair amount of time in Aizu. Morisada was approached by the [[Imperial Household Agency]] in the late 1980s, with a request to serve as an official at the mourning ceremony for [[Emperor Hirohito]]; simultaneously, they expressed a desire to install him as chief priest of [[Yasukuni Shrine]]. Morisada declined the Yasukuni appointment, as the shrine was built to enshrine the soldiers of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] who died in the [[Boshin War]] and exclude those who fought against them, including men of the [[Aizu]], [[Sendai Domain|Sendai]], [[Nihonmatsu Domain|Nihonmatsu]], and [[Morioka Domain|Morioka]] domains.<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.zaikai21.co.jp/zaifuku/back/0306.html 財界21 福島の経済情報誌「財界ふくしま」<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008133552/http://www.zaikai21.co.jp/zaifuku/back/0306.html |date=2007-10-08 }}</ref>

Morisada had one son, [[Morihisa Matsudaira]].<ref>Kobiyama Rokurō, ''Matsudaira Katamori no Shōgai: Shashinshu''. Tokyo: Shin Jinbutsu Ōraisha, 2003, p. 189</ref>

