{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Pakokku U Ohn Pe | native_name = {{my|ပခုက္ကူ ဦးအုန်းဖေ}} | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1917 | birth_place = Shadaw village, [[British Burma]] | death_date = {{death year and age|2008|1917}} | death_place = [[Pakokku]], [[Magwe Division]], [[Myanmar]] | nationality = Burmese | other_names = | pseudonyms = | known_for = | occupation = Writer, Businessman | parents = | spouse = | alma_mater = | awards = }}
'''Pakokku U Ohn Pe''' ({{lang-my|ပခုက္ကူ ဦးအုန်းဖေ}}; c. 1917 – 13 April 2008) was a [[Burma|Burmese]] businessman and writer who founded the prestigious [[Pakokku U Ohn Pe literary award]].
==Early years== U Ohn Pe was born around 1917 in Shardaw village near the town of [[Pakokku]]. He was the eldest of five siblings in a poor family. He only studied for a short time at a village monastery when he was about ten years old, learning basic reading and writing. He worked in various jobs including day labourer, betel nut seller, farm worker and timber worker. At the age of 29 he was arrested and thrown in prison for robbery. While he was in prison a sympathetic warden named U Maung Maung Tin helped U Ohn Pe develop an interest in reading.<ref name=Win20080504/>
==Businessman, philanthropist, writer==
After being released, U Ohn Pe started to deal in tobacco, and in 1956 was able to start his own tobacco manufacturing company and factory. As a successful businessman, he remained interested in literature. In 1992 he donated K7.6 million to set up the annual Pakokku U Ohn Pe Literary Award.<ref name=Win20080504/> The award is conferred annually for literary works considered the best in various genres.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phd-lit.arts.chula.ac.th/Download/ukinaye.pdf |title=Myanmar Post-colonial Literature |author=Khin Aye |publisher=Yangon University |year=2007 |accessdate=2012-02-21}}</ref> Later he founded the Pakokku U Ohn Pe Library in Pakokku. He also founded the Pakokku Outstanding Students Award, Pakokku Pharmaceutical Fund, Pakokku Fund for Fire and Pakokku Scholarship for the Poor.<ref name=Win20080504/>
U Ohn Pe visited China in 1996 with a delegation of Myanmar writers. In 2000 he published the first volume of his autobiography, with the second volume appearing in 2001 and the last in 2004.<ref name=Win20080504/> In November 2002 he won the [[Sayawun Tin Shwe Award]] for his ''Twaeya-kyonya-kyundaw-bawa'' (My experiences).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://missions.itu.int/~myanmar/02nlm/n021113.htm |title=Prizes presented to first Sayawun Tin Shwe Literary Award winners |work=New Light of Myanmar |date= 13 November 2002 |accessdate=2012-02-20}}</ref> He also published a collection of articles in 2004. He died on 13 April 2008 at Pakokku Hospital in [[Magwe Division]] aged 92.<ref name=Win20080504/> U Ohn Pe has been called the best known writer in Myanmar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200702/27/eng20070227_352759.html |date=February 27, 2007 |title=13 writers win U Ohn Pe manuscript awards in Myanmar |work=People's Daily |accessdate=2012-02-21}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist |refs= <ref name=Win20080504>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmtimes.com/no416/n006.htm |work=Myanmar Times |title=Literary patron U Ohn Pe dies |author=Nyunt Win |date=April 28 – May 4, 2008 |accessdate=2012-02-21}}</ref> }}
