{{Japanese name|Ikeda}}
[[File:Seihin Ikeda BOJ14.jpg|thumb|right|Seihin Ikeda]] 
{{nihongo|'''Seihin Ikeda''' or '''Shigeaki Ikeda'''|池田 成彬|Ikeda Seihin|August 15, 1867 &ndash; October 9, 1950}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] businessman and central banker.  He was the 14th Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ).<ref>Bank of Japan (BOJ), [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/sousai14.htm/ 14th Governor]</ref>

==Early life==
Ikeda was born at [[Yonezawa, Yamagata|Yonezawa]] in [[Yamagata Prefecture]].  He was educated at [[Keio University]]<ref name="nussbaum378">Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "Ikeda Seihin" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 378|page=378}}.</ref>  and [[Harvard University]], class of 1895.<ref>Thayer, William Roscoe ''et al.'' (1903). {{Google books|zDJYAAAAYAAJ|''The Harvard graduates' Magazine,'' Vol. 11, p. 275.|page=275}}</ref>

==Career==
Ikeda was a director of [[Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation|Mitsui Bank]] from 1909-1933.<ref name="nussbaum378"/>

From February 9, 1937 through July 27, 1937, Ikeda was Governor of the Bank of Japan.<ref>BOJ, [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/index.htm/ List of Governors].</ref>

In the first [[Konoe Fumimaro|Konoe]] cabinet, he served as Minister of Commerce and Industry.,<ref name="nussbaum378"/> and he was named [[Minister of Finance (Japan)|Minister of Finance]] in 1938.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0913FF3F55157A93CBAB178ED85F4C8385F9&scp=4&sq=Seihin%20Ikeda&st=cse  "Japanese May Altern Exchange Control; New Finance Minister Hopes to Aid Foreign Trade,"] ''New York Times.'' May 29, 1938; [https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/15/style/jun-makihara-an-investment-banker-and-mimi-oka-plan-to-marry-on-july-9.html?scp=1&sq=seihin%20ikeda&st=cse  "Jun Makihara, an Investment Banker, And Mimi Oka Plan to Marry on July 9,"] ''New York Times.'' May 15, 1988; retrieved 2011-08-22.</ref>

In 1941, he was made a member of the Imperial Privy Council; and for this reason, he was banned from all political activity after the end of the Pacific War.<ref name="nussbaum378"/>

